SIMPLE: pretor
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pretor
<hw>Pre"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praetor</ets>, for <ets>praeitor</ets>, fr. <ets>praeire</ets> to
go before; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>ire</ets> to go. See
<er>Issue</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A civil
officer or magistrate among the ancient Romans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Originally the <xex>pretor</xex> was a kind of third
consul; but at an early period two pretors were appointed, the first of
whom (<xex>praetor urbanus</xex>) was a kind of mayor or city judge; the
other (<xex>praetor peregrinus</xex>) was a judge of cases in which one
or both of the parties were foreigners. Still later, the number of
pretors, or judges, was further increased.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a mayor or magistrate.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pretorial</ent>⟦br⟧
